[49m[38;5;9m- 49    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m For a single ED, a sensible starting architecture is a Poisson regression with calendar and weather features for volume, plus a separate multinomial classifier for acuity mix. That gets you 80% of the available accuracy with a model the medical director can interrogate. Prophet is a strong second choice when you have several years of history and want to capture seasonality without engineering all the features by hand. DeepAR makes sense at scale, when you're standing up a forecast across dozens of EDs in a health system and want to share strength across them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m For a single ED, a sensible starting architecture is a Poisson regression with calendar and weather features for volume, plus a separate multinomial classifier for acuity mix. That gets you 80% of the available accuracy with a model the medical director can interrogate. Prophet is a strong second choice when you have several years of history and want to capture seasonality without engineering all the features by hand. DeepAR makes sense at scale, when you're standing up a forecast across dozens of EDs in a health system and want to share strength across them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **A note on multi-step forecasting strategy.** Poisson regression with engineered lag features (as described in Step 4 of the architecture companion) is iterated multi-step forecasting: the model predicts one hour at a time, feeds that prediction back as the lag input for the next hour, and errors compound across horizons. DeepAR, by contrast, is direct multi-step by construction: it produces the full forecast distribution across all future time steps in a single forward pass without recursive error accumulation. For the 4-hour operational horizon, the two strategies perform comparably because error compounding over four steps is modest. For 24-hour and 7-day horizons, direct multi-step methods are meaningfully more accurate because they avoid the snowball effect of feeding predictions back as inputs. If your primary operational decision is the 4-hour charge-nurse call-in, iterated Poisson regression is fine. If you're building shift-planning tools that depend on the 24-hour forecast, lean toward DeepAR or another direct multi-step method from the start.
